Yes, it is possible for a procedure to return a record by using the BYREF function. For example:
```
PROCEDURE ProcedureName(Parameter1)
    PARAMETERS Parameter1;
    VARIABLES Variable1:TYPE_OF_RECORD;
    RETURN Record;
END ProcedureName;
```

An external class can be defined using a procedure or method that has unnamed parameters. For example:
class myClass {
    *method* (***expression*** | **byref(***variable***)**) {
        do something with expression/variable...
    }
}

Yes, you can return records that have multiple fields by defining the type of the parameter as RECORD. For example:
```
PROCEDURE ProcedureName(Parameter1)
    PARAMETERS Parameter1;
    VARIABLES Variable1:RECORD;
END ProcedureName;
```

The Actian 4GL OpenROAD Unnamed Parameter List can be used to pass parameters in an external class. Here are some examples:
*Input Parameters:*
* Using the ** expression ** { , ** expression | ** byref( *** variable ***) **} syntax, where *expression* is an Actian 4GL OpenROAD expression and *variable* is any legal identifier.
```
CLASS MyClass
    METHOD MethodName(Parameter1, ByRef Variable2)
        PARAMETERS Parameter1, ByRef Variable2;
        DISPLAY "The value of the parameter is ", VARIABLE2.
    END MethodName;
END MyClass;
```
*Output Parameters:*
* Using a *byref( *** variable ***) ** expression to pass variables by reference. The value in the calling procedure or class will be changed by any changes made to the variable within the called procedure or method.
```
CLASS MyClass
    METHOD MethodName(ByRef Variable1, Parameter2)
        PARAMETERS ByRef Variable1, Parameter2;
        VARIABLE1 = Expression();
    END MethodName;
END MyClass;
```
